e</i> ‘spring, well’ (see   Fontaine  ), or a habitational name from any of several places mainly in the westcentral part of France so named. The surname <i>Fontenot</i> is very rare in France.","History: Jean-Louis Fonteneau/Fontenot from Montierneuf in Vienne, France, married Louise-Angélique Henry in Mobile, AL, in 1726."]},{"name":"Fontenelle","meanings":["French: topographic name from a diminutive of Old French <i>fontaine</i> ‘spring, well’ (see   Fontaine  ), or a habitational name from (La) Fontenelle, the name of several places in various parts of France, of the same origin."]},{"name":"Fontenette","meanings":["French: topographic name from a diminutive of Old French <i>fontaine</i> ‘spring, well’ (see   Fontaine  ), or a habitational name from Fontenette, the name of several places mainly in the central part of France, of the same origin."]},{"name":"Fountain","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from one or more of the places in France named Fontaine, Fonteyne, or Lafontaine (see   Fontaine  ).","English: topographic name for someone who lived near a spring or well, from Middle English <i>fontayne</i> (Old French <i>fontaine</i>) ‘spring, fountain’, sometimes with a plural <i>-s</i>, and synonymous with   Well  , of which <i>Fountain(es)</i> may sometimes have been a translation."]},{"name":"Font","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Juan, Luis, Miguel, Rafael, Eduardo, Raul, Eugenio, Pedro, Roberto, Aida.","Catalan and southern French: topographic name for someone living near a spring or well, Catalan and Occitan <i>font</i> ‘spring, well’ (from Latin <i>fons</i>, genitive <i>fontis</i>).","English: variant of   Fant  ."]},{"name":"Fontan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Angel, Benigno, Carlos, Jose, Juana, Manuel, Pedro, Adolfo, Aida, Alfredo, Candido, Emilia.","Spanish and Galician (<b>Fontán</b>): habitational name from any of the many places called Fontán, from <i>fontán</i> ‘spring’.","French: v